<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 6:2<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If4e762e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I1c3ad730933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>6.</label.designator><headtext>Selection of a Transferee District</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f37566e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>6:2.</label.designator><headtext>Limitations on choice of potential transferee districts</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>There are none.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>That answer may be too short for a treatise devoted to the Panel&apos;s work, but it is reasonably accurate. <eos/><bos/>For example, it is settled that the Panel can transfer actions to a district in which no action is then pending,[<footnote.reference refid="If4e789f06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] and that it can transfer to a district where venue could not properly be laid.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If4e7b1016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] Thus, the Panel can transfer all actions pending in federal courts to any district, regardless of where the actions are then pending.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel can also transfer actions to a district that no party suggests to the Panel.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If4e7b1026b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] Indeed, the Panel could transfer actions to a district that all parties agreed was not a desirable district. <eos/><bos/>The choice of a transferee district is thus properly viewed by the Panel, and should be by litigants, as a matter distinctly within the discretion of the Panel. <eos/><bos/>It is difficult to imagine that a decision of the Panel on selection of a transferee district would ever be reviewed by a court of appeals.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If4e7b1046b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In practice, however, the Panel rarely pushes these outer limits of its jurisdiction—it is far more likely to transfer a case to a district where at least one action is pending,[<footnote.reference refid="If4e7d8106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] or where a majority of the actions are pending,[<footnote.reference refid="If4e84d416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6</footnote.reference>] or where a mass disaster occurred.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If4e874516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If4e762e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If4e789f06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel has stated, however, a strong preference to transfer cases to a district where at least one action is already pending. <eos/><bos/>This preference and the Panel cases considering are discussed in greater detail in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:8" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If4e7b1006b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 6:8</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e7b1016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.,</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914063" w-serial-number="2005443059" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0004637" ID="I5df6f1c16b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Peanut Crop Ins. Litigation, 342 F. Supp. 2d 1353 (J.P.M.L. 2004)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914063" w-serial-number="1974104884" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I5df6f1c36b3e11e99779f698461214a6">In re Great Western Ranches Litigation, 369 F. Supp. 1406 (J.P.M.L. 1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e7b1026b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Despite its power to transfer cases to any district regardless of the preferences or even stipulations of the parties, the Panel generally does consider the parties&apos; views in selecting a transferee district. <eos/><bos/>This factor is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:18" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If4e7b1036b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 6:18</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e7b1046b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Appellate review of Panel decisions is discussed in detail in Chapter 11.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e7d8106b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:8" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If4e84d406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 6:8</cite.query>, below.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e84d416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:8" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If4e874506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 6:8</cite.query>, below.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If4e874516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:6" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If4e874526b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 6:6</cite.query>, below.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 6:2<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
